gy/Algebra/Order/MonotoneContinuity.lean#L67-L79","name":"continuousWithinAt_right_of_monotoneOn_of_exists_between","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/Order/MonotoneContinuity.html#continuousWithinAt_right_of_monotoneOn_of_exists_between","doc":"If `f` is a monotone function on a right neighborhood of `a` and the image of this neighborhood\nunder `f` meets every interval `(f a, b)`, `b > f a`, then `f` is continuous at `a` from the right.\n\nThe assumption `hfs : ∀ b > f a, ∃ c ∈ s, f c ∈ Ioo (f a) b` cannot be replaced by the weaker\nassumption `hfs : ∀ b > f a, ∃ c ∈ s, f c ∈ Ioc (f a) b` we use for strictly monotone functions\nbecause otherwise the function `ceil : ℝ → ℤ` would be a counter-example at `a = 0`. "},{"sourceLink":"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/44c828ca5b12983ef1d4eea5c54f95c2ef52cb36/Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/Order/MonotoneContinuity.lean#L46-L58","name":"StrictMonoOn.continuousWithinAt_right_of_exists_between","kind":"theorem","docLink":"./Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/Order/MonotoneContinuity.html#StrictMonoOn.continuousWithinAt_right_of_exists_between","doc":"If `f` is a function strictly monotone on a right neighborhood of `a` and the\nimage of this neighborhood under `f` meets every interval `(f a, b]`, `b > f a`, then `f` is\ncontinuous at `a` from the right.\n\nThe assumption `hfs : ∀ b > f a, ∃ c ∈ s, f c ∈ Ioc (f a) b` is required because otherwise the\nfunction `f : ℝ → ℝ` given by `f x = if x ≤ 0 then x else x + 1` would be a counter-example at\n`a = 0`. "}]}